SIMPLE: meed
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meed
<hw>Meed</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mede</ets>, AS. <ets>m⟦emac⟧d</ets>, <ets>meord</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>m⟦emac⟧da</ets>, OHG. <ets>miata</ets>, <ets>mieta</ets>, G.
<ets>miethe</ets> hire, Goth. <ets>mizd⟦omac⟧</ets> reward, Bohem. &
Russ. <ets>mzda</ets>, Gr. <grk>misqo`s</grk>, Skr.
<ets>m⟦imac⟧dha</ets>. ⟦root⟧276.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
bestowed or rendered in consideration of merit; reward;
recompense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A rosy garland was the victor's <qex>meed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Merit or desert; worth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>meed</qex> hath got me fame.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gift; also, a bride.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Meed
<hw>Meed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reward; to
repay.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Waytt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deserve; to merit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Heywood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meedful</ent>⟦br⟧
